"{\"Course Name\": \"GLOBAL ENVIRONMENTAL HISTORY\", \"Course Level\": \"2403\", \"Dept Abbreviation\": \"HI\", \"Course Description\": \"Cat. II\\nThis course will introduce students to global environmental history, a field that examines how the environment has shaped human society, and the effects of human activity and human ideas on non-human nature. The course will trace human history from hunter-gather societies to the present, addressing changes in production, trade, and consumption patterns; transportation and other technologies; science, knowledge, and planning; disease, health and medicine; and cultural understandings, political debates, and place-making strategies. This course is appropriate for students interested in WPI's project centers in Africa, Asia, and the Caribbean and Central America.\\nThis course can be offered in 2016-17, and in alternating years thereafter.\", \"Requirements\": [], \"Is Cat 1\": false, \"Start Year For Cat 2\": \"2016\"}"